library(curl)
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)

Part One

Using the KamilarAndCooperData.csv dataset, run a linear regression looking at log(HomeRange_km2) in relation to log(Body_mass_female_mean) and report your coeffiecients (slope and intercept).

Import the Data Set

f <- curl("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/fuzzyatelin/fuzzyatelin.github.io/master/AN588_Fall23/KamilarAndCooperData.csv")
d <- read.csv(f, header = TRUE, sep = ",", stringsAsFactors = FALSE) #Assign D as the vector for the data set

Determine the Intercept(B0) and Slope (B1) by Calling The Information

mI <-  lm(log(HomeRange_km2) ~ log(Body_mass_female_mean), data = d)
summary(mI)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log(HomeRange_km2) ~ log(Body_mass_female_mean), 
##     data = d)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -3.3929 -0.9433 -0.0126  1.0944  3.6826 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                            Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)                -9.44123    0.67293  -14.03   <2e-16 ***
## log(Body_mass_female_mean)  1.03643    0.08488   12.21   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.423 on 135 degrees of freedom
##   (76 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5248, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5213 
## F-statistic: 149.1 on 1 and 135 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The Slope of This Linear Regression is 1.03643, and the intercept is -9.44123.

Plot and Add A Fitted Line Using ggplot2

h <- ggplot(data = d, aes(x = log(HomeRange_km2), y = log(Body_mass_female_mean)))
h <- h + geom_point()
h <- h + geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ x)
h + annotate("text", x = 2, y = 6.5, label = "y=1.03643 x - 9.44123")


Part Two

Then, use bootstrapping to sample from your data 1000 times with replacement, each time fitting the same model and calculating the same coefficients. This generates a sampling distribution for each coefficient.

Also do the following:

  • Estimate the standard error for each of your coefficients as the standard deviation of the sampling distribution from your bootstrap and determine the 95% CI for each of your coefficients based on the appropriate quantiles from your sampling distribution.

  • How does the former compare to the SE estimated from your entire dataset using the formula for standard error implemented in lm()?

  • How does the latter compare to the 95% CI estimated from your entire dataset?
